06027nam a22008655i 9780824865382DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20012001hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248653827 a10.1515/97808248653822doi  a(DE-B1597)483856  a(OCoLC)1024020961  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHQ1075.5.K6bU53 2002eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.3/09519522100aUnder Construction :bThe Gendering of Modernity, Class, and Consumption in the Republic of Korea /ced. by Laurel Kendall. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Women, Mobility, and Desire: Narrating Class and Gender in South Korea -- t3. Discourses of Illness, Meanings of Modernity: A Gendered Construction of Sŏnginbyŏng -- t4. The Production and Subversion of Hegemonic Masculinity: Reconfiguring Gender Hierarchy in Contemporary South Korea -- t5. Gender Construction in the Offices of a South Korean Conglomerate -- t6. The Concept of Female Sexuality in Korean Popular Culture -- t7. Living With Conflicting Subjectivities: Mother, Motherly Wife, and Sexy Woman in the Transition From Colonial-Modern to Postmodern Korea -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the late 1960s, the lives of south Koreans have been reconstructed on the shifting ground of urbanization, industrialization, military authoritarianism, democratic reform, and social liberalization. Class and gender identities have been modified in relation to a changing modernity and new definitions of home and family, work and leisure, husband and wife. Under Construction provides an illuminating portrait of south Koreans in the 1990s--a decade that saw a return to civilian rule, a loosening of censorship and social control, and the emergence of a full-blown consumer culture. It shows how these changes impacted the lives of Korean men and women and the very definition of what it means to be "male" and "female" in Korea. In a series of provocative essays written by Korean and Western scholars, we see how Korean women and men actively engage, and at times openly contest, the limitations of gender. Under Construction is part of a decisive turn in the anthropology of gender--from its early quest for the causes of female subordination to a finely tuned analysis of the historical, cultural, and class-based specificities of gender relations and the tension between gender as an ideological construct and as a lived experience. Firmly grounded in the political and economic history of south Korea, this long-awaited volume fills an important gap in Korean studies and East Asia gender studies in English. Contributors: Nancy Abelmann, Cho Haejoang, Roger L. Janelli, Laurel Kendall, June Lee, So-Hee Lee, Seungsook Moon, Dawnhee Yim.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFemininityzKorea (South). 0aMasculinityzKorea (South). 0aSex rolezKorea (South). 0aSocial classeszKorea (South). 0aWomenzKorea (South)xSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aAbelmann, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaejoang, Cho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanelli, Roger L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKendall, Laurel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKendall, Laurel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, June J. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, So-Hee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/